<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,1293,1935]" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,494,1622,1647]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" reason="1">Justification of the synonymy.</emphasis>
The epigynum of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1887" box="[696,816,1623,1646]" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Aracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="captator">
<emphasis box="[696,712,1623,1646]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[726,816,1623,1646]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">captator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
looks similar to the epigynum of the 
<emphasis box="[1226,1365,1622,1646]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">subterraneus</emphasis>
-group of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1848" box="[181,258,1658,1682]" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Zelotes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[181,258,1658,1682]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Zelotes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as illustrated for 
<taxonomicName authority="(C. L. Koch, 1833)" baseAuthorityName="C. L. Koch" baseAuthorityYear="1833" box="[453,891,1658,1683]" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Zelotes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subterraneus">
<emphasis box="[453,677,1658,1682]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Zelotes subterraneus</emphasis>
(C. L. 
<bibRefCitation author="Koch, C. L." box="[755,884,1658,1683]" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" pagination="119 - 121" refId="ref1146" refString="Koch, C. L. (1833) Arachniden. In: Herrich-Schaffer, G. A. W. (Ed.), Deutschlands Insecten. Heft. Friedrich Pustet, Regensburg, pp. 119 - 121. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 15007" type="book chapter" year="1833">Koch, 1833</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Chamberlin, 1920" authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1920" box="[903,1254,1658,1683]" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Zelotes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fratris">
<emphasis box="[903,1054,1658,1682]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Zelotes fratris</emphasis>
Chamberlin, 1920
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Lowrie &amp; Gertsch, 1955" authorityName="Lowrie &amp; Gertsch" authorityYear="1955" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Zelotes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sula">
<emphasis box="[1307,1436,1658,1682]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Zelotes sula</emphasis>
Lowrie &amp; Gertsch, 1955
</taxonomicName>
: epigynum with paired anterior comma-like margins, with L-shaped lateral margins and posterior margin with a median protrusion (compare 
<figureCitation box="[614,676,1730,1754]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[182,1401,183,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-16@1.[181,1406,180,1912]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Zelotes captator (Thorell, 1887) comb. nov., holotype female of Aracus captator Thorell, 1887 (MSNG). 1 habitus, dorsal view; 2 eye group, dorsal view; 3 right chelicera, retrolateral view; 4 anterior lateral spinnerets, ventral view; 5 epigynum, ventral view; 6 original labels in the holotype vial. All figures not to scale. © MSNG, Genova, Italy." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6332523" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6332523/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
with 
<bibRefCitation author="Platnick, N. I. &amp; Shadab, M. U." box="[737,1001,1730,1755]" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" pagination="97 - 192" refId="ref1277" refString="Platnick, N. I. &amp; Shadab, M. U. (1983) A revision of the American spiders of the genus Zelotes (Araneae, Gnaphosidae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 174, 97 - 192." type="journal article" year="1983">Platnick &amp; Shadab 1983</bibRefCitation>
: figs 4, 8, 11, 16). Moreover, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1887" box="[1316,1436,1731,1754]" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Aracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="captator">
<emphasis box="[1316,1332,1731,1754]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1346,1436,1731,1754]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">captator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has small, globular spermathecae that are also similar to that of the above-mentioned species (compare 
<figureCitation box="[1261,1324,1766,1790]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[182,1401,183,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-16@1.[181,1406,180,1912]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Zelotes captator (Thorell, 1887) comb. nov., holotype female of Aracus captator Thorell, 1887 (MSNG). 1 habitus, dorsal view; 2 eye group, dorsal view; 3 right chelicera, retrolateral view; 4 anterior lateral spinnerets, ventral view; 5 epigynum, ventral view; 6 original labels in the holotype vial. All figures not to scale. © MSNG, Genova, Italy." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6332523" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6332523/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
with 
<bibRefCitation author="Platnick, N. I. &amp; Shadab, M. U." pageId="0" pageNumber="145" pagination="97 - 192" refId="ref1277" refString="Platnick, N. I. &amp; Shadab, M. U. (1983) A revision of the American spiders of the genus Zelotes (Araneae, Gnaphosidae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 174, 97 - 192." type="journal article" year="1983">Platnick &amp; Shadab 1983</bibRefCitation>
: figs 4, 8, 11, 16). Based on these observations, I propose to consider 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1887" box="[1134,1210,1803,1826]" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Aracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1134,1210,1803,1826]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Aracus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1848" box="[180,257,1838,1862]" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Zelotes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[180,257,1838,1862]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Zelotes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in contrast to 
<bibRefCitation author="Deeleman-Reinhold, C. L." box="[418,714,1838,1863]" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" refId="ref1033" refString="Deeleman-Reinhold, C. L. (2001) Forest spiders of South East Asia: with a revision of the sac and ground spiders (Araneae: Clubionidae, Corinnidae, Liocranidae, Gnaphosidae, Prodidomidae and Trochanterriidae [sic]). Brill, Leiden, 591 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 9789004475588" type="book" year="2001">Deeleman-Reinhold (2001)</bibRefCitation>
, who doubted 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1887" box="[871,947,1839,1862]" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Aracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[871,947,1839,1862]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Aracus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a senior synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="Chamberlin, 1922" authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1922" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1208,1356,1838,1862]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Haplodrassus</emphasis>
Chamberlin, 1922
</taxonomicName>
. Females of 
<taxonomicName authority="Chamberlin, 1922" authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1922" box="[425,573,1874,1898]" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[425,573,1874,1898]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Haplodrassus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are distinct from that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1887" box="[934,1010,1875,1898]" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Aracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[934,1010,1875,1898]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="145">Aracus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having paired lateral epigynal arms (
<bibRefCitation author="Platnick, N. I. &amp; Shadab, M. U." box="[158,424,1910,1935]" pageId="0" pageNumber="145" pagination="1 - 40" refId="ref1233" refString="Platnick, N. I. &amp; Shadab, M. U. (1975) A revision of the spider genera Haplodrassus and Orodrassus (Araneae, Gnaphosidae) in North America. American Museum Novitates, 2583, 1 - 40." type="journal article" year="1975">Platnick &amp; Shadab 1975</bibRefCitation>
: figs 3, 7). The proposed synonymy has resulted in a new combination (see below).
</paragraph>
